s involved, illuminating how psychological research either supports or opposes the legal principles in question, and placing particular emphasis on the areas that are still in need of further research. The volume identifies areas where psychology practice and research already have been or could be useful in molding legal doctrine and policy, and by providing psychology researchers with new ideas for legally relevant research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDomestic relationsxPsychological aspects. 0aDomestic relations. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Applied Psychology.2bisacsh  aabortion.  aadoption.  aalimony.  aalternative dispute resolution.  aassisted reproductive technology.  acaregiving.  achild maltreatment.  achild support.  acognitive biases.  acohabitation.  acontraception.  acouples counseling.  acustody.  adissolution.  adivorce.  aeducational requirements.  aelder maltreatment.  aincest.  aintimate partner.  amandatory reporting.  amarital privilege.  amarriage law.  amodern parenting.  anonmarriage.  aparental responsibility.  apolygamy.  apremarital.  aprenuptial agreements.  aproperty.  aseparation.  asolemnization.  asurnames.  aviolence.  awrongful adoption.  awrongful birth.1 aDemaine, Linda J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479865413.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479882601423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479882601/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles